{#- DEFINITION — plain-terms prose body -#}
<section class="sec reveal" id="qb-help-bank-feed-disconnected-definition" style="padding-top:24px;">
  <div class="ct read read--doc">
    <div class="eyebrow" style="margin-bottom:8px;">In plain terms</div>
    <h2 class="h2" style="margin-bottom:18px;">&ldquo;Bank feed disconnected,&rdquo; plainly.</h2>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>A bank feed is the live connection between your bank or credit-card account and QuickBooks that downloads transactions automatically. When that connection shows as <em>disconnected</em> &mdash; or flags &ldquo;needs attention,&rdquo; &ldquo;action required,&rdquo; or keeps asking you to sign in again &mdash; the feed has lost the authorization that lets QuickBooks pull from the bank on your behalf. New transactions stop arriving until you re-establish it. This is the narrower cousin of a feed that&rsquo;s simply not updating: here the connection itself has dropped, and the cure is re-authentication, not a refresh.</p>
      <p>Most disconnects trace to something the <em>bank</em> changed &mdash; a password or security update, a new multi-factor step, or a move to a different feed provider &mdash; that invalidated the old connection. The reconnect steps below address those in order of likelihood, and re-entering your sign-in info plus completing the bank&rsquo;s re-authentication clears a large share of cases. What reconnecting <em>can&rsquo;t</em> fix is the bookkeeping the outage left behind: the gap of dates that never downloaded, duplicates created when the feed came back, and a reconciliation that no longer ties. That part is a ProAdvisor job. And if the disconnect is an Intuit account matter or a bank-side outage, that&rsquo;s theirs to resolve &mdash; not something we can reach.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

